ry in consumer society, financial capitalism, and virtual culture. For Kierkegaard, by contrast, Luther’s God remains radically transcendent, while finite human beings and their world remain fully dependent. From this insight, Heidegger and Derrida developed an alternative view of time in which a radically open future breaks into the present to transform the past, demonstrating that, far from autonomous, life is a gift from an Other that can never be known. Offering an alternative genealogy of deconstruction that traces its pedigree back to readings of Paul by way of Luther, Abiding Grace presents a thoroughgoing critique of modernity and postmodernity’s will to power and mastery. In this new philosophical and theological vision, history is not over and the future remains endlessly open.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPostmodernismxReligious aspects. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aconsumer culture.  adeath.  adeconstruction.  agrace.  amodernism.  aposthumanism.  apostmodernism.  asecularism.  astructuralism.  atime.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226569116423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226569116/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles